in-Barr virus","Human Immunodeficiency Virus","Rhinovirus","Poliovirus","Measles virus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EHuman Immunodeficiency Virus\u003C/strong\u003E specifically targets CD4+ T helper cells and requires both CD4 and chemokine receptors (particularly CCR5 and CXCR4) for cell entry. This dual receptor requirement is essential for viral fusion and infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other viruses use different receptors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily infects B lymphocytes through CD21 receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERhinovirus\u003C/strong\u003E enters respiratory epithelial cells using intercellular adhesion molecule 1 (ICAM-1)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoliovirus\u003C/strong\u003E enters cells using the poliovirus receptor CD155\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles virus\u003C/strong\u003E uses CD46 and signaling lymphocytic activation molecule (SLAM) as cellular receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe specific receptor usage of each virus determines which cell types it can infect, known as viral tropism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) specifically targets CD4+ T helper cells using CD4 and chemokine receptors for cell entry","CD4 and chemokine receptors (particularly CCR5 and CXCR4) are essential co-receptors for HIV infection of T helper cells","Different viruses use distinct cellular receptors for entry - this determines their cell tropism"],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Naif HM. Pathogenesis of HIV Infection. Infect Dis Rep. 2013 Jun 6;5(Suppl 1):e6. doi: 10.4081/idr.2013.s1.e6. PMID: 24470970; PMCID: PMC3892619.","Lackner AA, Lederman MM, Rodriguez B. HIV pathogenesis: the host. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012 Sep 1;2(9):a007005. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a007005. PMID: 22951442; PMCID: PMC3426821."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51906"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51906"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T09:47:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T09:48:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7651"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66455"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synony